6.1 À but lucratif (abordable, prix du marché)

Curbcut

6.1.1 Développement résidentiel récent (répartition territoriale par type de logement et typologie)

Data source: CMHC Starts and Completions Survey.

Since 1990, the number of annual housing completions in Laval has remained relatively level, albeit with high levels of year-to-year fluctuation. The five-year period with the most completions has been 2006-2010, when there was an average of 3015.4 housing units completed each year. By contrast, in the period 1995-1999 only 1264.2 housing units were completed on average each year.

Années Unifamilial Jumelé En rangée Appartement Total
1990-1993 1 018 423 181 689 2 310
1994-1998 784 202 126 179 1 290
1999-2003 1 244 95 77 545 1 960
2004-2008 1 166 147 118 1 451 2 880
2009-2013 550 98 150 1 546 2 340
2014-2018 184 45 106 1 221 1 560
2019-2023 171 13 32 2 036 2 250

Prior to 2000, most newly constructed housing in Laval comprised single-family homes, with some semi-detached homes also being constructed particularly in the early 1990s. However, since 2000, there has been a substantial shift away from single-detached homes and towards apartments. Annual single-family housing completions peaked in 2003 and have been declining every year since (albeit with minor fluctuations). By contrast, since 2000 apartment completions have surged, with a five-year moving average demonstrating ongoing increases in the total number of apartments entering the market each year.

There have been no meaningful semi-detached housing completions since the early 1990s, and row houses have consistently been a negligible portion of total completions.

The same basic trends are evident looking at housing completions by intended market instead of dwelling type. Homeowner housing completions have steadily declined since a recent peak in the early 2000s. Rental and condominium completions are much more volatile—reflecting a smaller number of large projects. Both increased from near-zero levels in the 1990s. In the case of condominiums, completions began rising in the late 2000s, peaked in 2010, and have since been declining. Rental completions, by contrast, began increasing in the late 2000s and have been increasing ever since. 31,2 % of all Laval housing completions since 2015 have been intended for the rental market. There have been no co-operative housing completions in Laval in the period of time that CMHC has tracked this information.

Both in absolute and per-dwelling terms, housing development has been concentrated in the southern Chomedey/Sainte-Dorothée region of Laval. This pattern has remained relatively consistent 2009, although was particularly extreme in the 2014-2018 period, where 55,2 % of all new housing completions were in the Chomedey/Sainte-Dorothée zone.

6.1.2 Mises en chantier par typologie

Data source: CMHC Starts and Completions Survey.

Since 1990, housing starts in Laval have varied cyclically, with three distinct peaks and troughs. Rolling five-year averages of housing starts peaked in 1990, 2007 and 2020 at 2 320, 3 050 and 2 310 respectively, and bottomed out at 1997, 2014 and 2023 at 1 260, 1 570 and 1 940 respectively. (However, although 2023 saw a recent low in housing starts, it is likely that the five-year average will continue to decline for the next several years, given the fact that only 1 170) housing units were initiated in 2023.

Période Total Unifamilial Semi-détaché En rangée Appartement
1990-1993 2 228 1 005 426 195 602
1994-1998 1 297 797 192 126 182
1999-2003 2 159 1 321 100 71 666
2004-2008 3 048 1 112 146 143 1 648
2009-2013 2 327 515 95 126 1 591
2014-2018 1 764 174 42 96 1 451
2019-2023 2 074 177 13 35 1 849

Avant 2000, la majorité des logements nouvellement construits à Laval étaient des maisons individuelles, bien que quelques maisons jumelées aient également été construites, surtout au début des années 1990. Cependant, depuis 2000, les maisons individuelles ont été largement abandonnées au profit des appartements. Le nombre de logements unifamiliaux achevés a atteint son apogée en 2002, avant de diminuer chaque année par la suite, avec quelques fluctuations mineures. En revanche, depuis 2000, le nombre d’appartements achevés a fortement augmenté. On the one hand, apartment starts have followed the same broad trends as overall housing starts, with a peak in the mid-2000s and another peak in 2020. On the other hand, driven by a collapse in non-apartment housing starts, apartment projects have been steadily increasing as a proportion of total starts. Every year since 2005, apartment projects have been a majority of all housing starts, and every year since 2015 they have been three quarters or more of all starts.

In both absolute and per-dwelling terms, new housing starts have consistently been highest in the southern part of the city—particularly in the Chomedey/Sainte-Dorothée zone—and lowest in the eastern part of the island.

6.1.3 Mises en chantier par mode d’occupation

Data source: CMHC Starts and Completions Survey.

Les mises en chantier montrent des tendances similaires lorsqu’elles sont ventilées par marché cible. Les taux élevés de nouveaux projets de logements destinés à l’accession à la propriété dans les années 1990 et 2000 ont progressivement laissé place aux mises en chantier de logements en copropriété et, plus récemment, à celles de logements locatifs. Looking at five-year moving averages, homeowner starts peaked in 2000-2004 at 1 560 per year. Condominium starts peaked in 2008-2012 at 1 130 per year. And rental starts peaked in 2018-2022 at 1 780 per year.

Période Prop.-occ. Locatif Copropriété Coopératif Total
1990-1993 1 470 316 442 0 2 228
1994-1998 1 057 92 148 0 1 297
1999-2003 1 437 150 572 0 2 159
2004-2008 1 316 804 918 11 3 048
2009-2013 735 558 1 025 9 2 327
2014-2018 301 658 805 0 1 764
2019-2023 224 1 598 251 0 2 074

Mirroring the shift discussed in 6.1.2 towards apartment housing starts, sine 2010 an increasingly high percentage of annual housing starts have been intended for the rental market, albeit with a high level of volatility. This trend largely reflects the interaction between a highly cyclical rental construction sector (with peaks in starts in 2007-2008 and 2020), a long-term decline in new starts in the homeownership sector, and the 2000s growth and then 2010s decline in condominium starts.
